00:34:17,740 --> 00:34:19,241
and we felt the consequences of that.

765
00:34:19,841 --> 00:34:21,142
You can see on this chart that

766
00:34:21,362 --> 00:34:23,503
the return rate after the launch of the combat,

767
00:34:23,683 --> 00:34:24,583
the new combat system,

768
00:34:25,004 --> 00:34:27,024
doesn't get the normal seasonal rise.

769
00:34:27,045 --> 00:34:29,346
So there's a difference between the red and the blue there.

770
00:34:30,646 --> 00:34:33,988
For some returners, the change was simply too great all at once,

771
00:34:34,268 --> 00:34:35,949
and they simply stopped coming back.

772
00:34:36,670 --> 00:34:38,711
And we were fortunate we were able to recover this

773
00:34:38,951 --> 00:34:41,552
with the legacy combat mode I mentioned earlier.

774
00:34:42,173 --> 00:34:43,934
But honestly, if we'd made better decisions,

775
00:34:44,334 --> 00:34:45,174
it wouldn't have been needed,

776
00:34:45,235 --> 00:34:47,516
and we could have put that effort into other things.

777
00:34:50,594 --> 00:34:55,121
By contrast, in early 2012, we launched a feature that could have been similarly disruptive.

778
00:34:55,501 --> 00:34:56,863
It was called the Squeal of Fortune.

779
00:34:57,324 --> 00:35:02,672
It was a mystery box style minigame where you could spin a prize wheel, get things like

780
00:35:02,832 --> 00:35:05,416
in-game resources, XP boosts, or currency.

781
00:35:07,027 --> 00:35:11,209
It was a daily login incentives where players were given a couple of free spins every day,

782
00:35:11,649 --> 00:35:16,092
but they could also buy additional spins as a microtransaction option.

783
00:35:16,492 --> 00:35:20,033
And this was the first time, to that point in the game's ten-year history,

784
00:35:20,093 --> 00:35:23,775
when payments beyond the subscription could get you any sort of benefit.

785
00:35:24,616 --> 00:35:26,156
And it did cause quite a stir,

786
00:35:26,236 --> 00:35:27,257
and there were some complaints,

787
00:35:28,077 --> 00:35:30,838
but it actually had zero impact on either our existing

788
00:35:30,958 --> 00:35:32,259
or our returning player numbers.

789
00:35:32,279 --> 00:35:34,840
And I believe this was because it fundamentally

790
00:35:34,900 --> 00:35:36,561
didn't change the core of the game.

791
00:35:37,181 --> 00:35:39,042
While some players didn't like it in principle,

792
00:35:39,422 --> 00:35:42,184
it was in reality a fairly mild implementation

793
00:35:42,264 --> 00:35:43,184
of an MTX feature,

794
00:35:43,464 --> 00:35:45,045
and it didn't change the way people played.

795
00:35:46,266 --> 00:35:47,986
So, of course, you can make changes.

796
00:35:48,246 --> 00:35:49,487
You can make big changes,

797
00:35:49,727 --> 00:35:51,548
even deep into a product's lifecycle.

798
00:35:51,928 --> 00:35:53,709
But I think caution is needed.

799
00:35:55,475 --> 00:35:57,736
So my recommendations for managing change are

800
00:35:58,516 --> 00:36:01,117
to alter core gameplay at your peril.

801
00:36:01,677 --> 00:36:03,098
Undermining the player's mastery,

802
00:36:03,518 --> 00:36:04,699
devaluing their achievements,

803
00:36:04,859 --> 00:36:06,939
or altering how they fundamentally approach the game

804
00:36:06,979 --> 00:36:09,740
can be disastrous if not handled really carefully.

805
00:36:11,510 --> 00:36:12,811
When you're considering a big change,

806
00:36:12,991 --> 00:36:15,833
do thorough research and testing across all types of players,

807
00:36:15,913 --> 00:36:18,436
not just those you're targeting with a specific feature.

808
00:36:19,216 --> 00:36:22,319
Give yourself enough time to test and iterate before launch,

809
00:36:22,759 --> 00:36:25,321
and give yourself the option to change course

810
00:36:25,361 --> 00:36:26,723
if you're seeing warning signals.

811
00:36:28,784 --> 00:36:30,926
Also, be on the lookout for cumulative change.

812
00:36:31,567 --> 00:36:33,048
Again, RuneScape is on the extreme end

813
00:36:33,088 --> 00:36:34,689
because we update pretty much every week,

814
00:36:35,190 --> 00:36:36,571
but it's something you should keep an eye on

815
00:36:36,691 --> 00:36:38,372
even if you've got a lower update cadence.

816
00:36:39,360 --> 00:36:41,741
I recommend not just looking at the change per release,

817
00:36:42,021 --> 00:36:44,523
but looking at how it's adding up over a longer period.

818
00:36:46,804 --> 00:36:48,305
And if you are making a big change,

819
00:36:48,525 --> 00:36:50,126
consider whether you can add some sort

820
00:36:50,206 --> 00:36:51,527
of backwards compatibility.

821
00:36:52,147 --> 00:36:53,648
I mentioned earlier how we re-added

822
00:36:53,688 --> 00:36:56,790
RuneScape's old combat and UI in alternate legacy mode.

823
00:36:57,290 --> 00:36:59,211
And I wish we'd included that in the first place.

824
00:37:02,802 --> 00:37:04,983
Managing community sentiment is just as important

825
00:37:05,023 --> 00:37:08,624
because player satisfaction has a real impact on returners.

826
00:37:09,465 --> 00:37:12,666
If the player base are annoyed and outraged,

827
00:37:12,746 --> 00:37:14,447
there's going to be less positive word of mouth

828
00:37:14,867 --> 00:37:16,888
reaching lapsed players outside the game,

829
00:37:17,408 --> 00:37:19,949
and that's going to reduce the number of them likely to return.

830
00:37:21,249 --> 00:37:23,230
And inside the game, negative sentiment

831
00:37:23,290 --> 00:37:24,551
turns into toxic chatter,

832
00:37:25,011 --> 00:37:26,391
and that won't be pleasant for the returners

833
00:37:26,431 --> 00:37:27,812
who have made it back into the game,

834
00:37:27,952 --> 00:37:29,693
and it will harm their re-engagement.

835
00:37:30,879 --> 00:37:34,322
To stay on top of these risks, I recommend finding ways

836
00:37:34,742 --> 00:37:36,524
to track community sentiment, to stay

837
00:37:36,564 --> 00:37:37,785
aware of how players are feeling,

838
00:37:38,545 --> 00:37:40,267
and use it to calibrate your design decisions

839
00:37:40,467 --> 00:37:41,347
to do things about it.

840
00:37:42,548 --> 00:37:43,970
And we use a number of methods for this,

841
00:37:44,010 --> 00:37:46,872
but I'll show you two of the most relevant ones.

842
00:37:47,773 --> 00:37:50,555
This first one is a weekly community sentiment report

843
00:37:50,875 --> 00:37:53,037
that's put together by our community management team.

844
00:37:53,797 --> 00:37:56,199
It talks about how the players are reacting to that week's

845
00:37:56,239 --> 00:37:57,640
new content and events.

846
00:37:58,743 --> 00:38:02,105
It shows the split of opinion from players across their game,

847
00:38:02,225 --> 00:38:05,266
our forums, social media, and it calls out specific issues

848
00:38:05,646 --> 00:38:07,507
and makes recommendations for addressing them.

849
00:38:08,028 --> 00:38:10,089
This gives us a really good short-term view

850
00:38:10,189 --> 00:38:11,430
of the issues, the sentiment,

851
00:38:11,810 --> 00:38:14,031
and allows us to react quickly when we need to.

852
00:38:16,641 --> 00:38:18,742
The other method is a much longer form

853
00:38:18,842 --> 00:38:20,383
customer satisfaction tracker.

854
00:38:21,003 --> 00:38:22,484
We survey our players every month

855
00:38:22,604 --> 00:38:24,565
to see what they think about the game and the service,

856
00:38:25,066 --> 00:38:28,547
and it allows us to see the importance of each sub area

857
00:38:28,808 --> 00:38:30,889
and how much it affects their future behaviors.

858
00:38:31,369 --> 00:38:33,590
So this type of analysis allows us to measure

859
00:38:33,610 --> 00:38:36,192
the business impact of player sentiment

860
00:38:36,552 --> 00:38:37,792
and how it affects things like

861
00:38:37,912 --> 00:38:39,553
recommendations and word of mouth.

862
00:38:41,343 --> 00:38:43,965
So maybe it's obvious, but this shows empirically

863
00:38:44,846 --> 00:38:47,227
keeping your customers happy is good for the bottom line.

864
00:38:47,788 --> 00:38:50,730
And it will help you in getting and keeping

865
00:38:50,970 --> 00:38:52,411
more returning players.

866
00:38:52,431 --> 00:38:57,855
I've gone through quite a lot today, so I'll wrap up

867
00:38:58,116 --> 00:38:59,737
and recap on the key points.

868
00:39:00,938 --> 00:39:03,620
Returners are increasingly important as your game ages.

869
00:39:03,820 --> 00:39:06,142
So start building them into your design considerations

870
00:39:06,322 --> 00:39:07,343
as early as you can.

871
00:39:08,859 --> 00:39:13,002
Utilize social media as a way to communicate with LAPS players on their terms.

872
00:39:13,442 --> 00:39:18,085
Don't just rely on email, and empower players to get the word out on your behalf.

873
00:39:19,706 --> 00:39:23,990
Try to have some game updates designed specifically around the needs of LAPS players,

874
00:39:24,490 --> 00:39:28,393
and then launch these at the start of seasonal uplifts in Returners.

875
00:39:30,394 --> 00:39:32,776
Help Returners regain their mastery of the game.

876
00:39:32,916 --> 00:39:34,457
Don't just leave them to get on with it alone,

877
00:39:35,058 --> 00:39:37,920
and ideally find ways to give them personalized catch-up.

878
00:39:40,338 --> 00:39:42,619
When you've got them playing, deepen their engagement

879
00:39:42,639 --> 00:39:43,960
with special community events,

880
00:39:44,141 --> 00:39:45,782
which are designed sympathetically

881
00:39:46,042 --> 00:39:47,263
to their available time.

882
00:39:49,064 --> 00:39:51,406
And manage the rate of change cautiously,

883
00:39:51,966 --> 00:39:53,287
especially in core gameplay.

884
00:39:53,947 --> 00:39:55,328
Keep track of community sentiment

885
00:39:55,468 --> 00:39:56,829
and use it to guide your decisions

886
00:39:57,410 --> 00:39:59,952
and always keep players as happy as possible.

